[[File:Electric feed rocket cycle.svg|thumb|right|250px|Electric-feed rocket cycle. The oxidizer and fuel are fed to the pump which increases the pressure before injecting it into the combustion chamber. The pumps are actuated by an electric motor powered by batteries. An inverter converts the batteries' DC electricity to the AC needed by the motor. The fuel is also circulated around the outside of the combustion chamber and nozzle to prevent them overheating.]]
The '''electric-pump-fed engine''' is a [[bipropellant rocket]] [[rocket engine|engine]] in which the fuel pumps are electrically powered, and so all of the input propellant is directly burned in the main combustion chamber, and none is diverted to drive the pumps. This differs from traditional rocket engine designs, in which the pumps are driven by a portion of the input propellants.
An electric cycle engine uses electric [[pump]]s to pressurize the propellants from a low-pressure fuel tank to high-pressure [[Rocket engine#Combustion chamber|combustion chamber]] levels, generally from {{convert|0.2|to|0.3|MPa|abbr=on}} to {{convert|10|to|20|MPa|abbr=on}}. The pumps are powered by an [[electric motor]], with electricity from a battery bank.
As of January 2018, the only rocket engines to use electric [[Liquid-propellant rocket|propellant]] pump systems are the [[Rutherford (rocket engine)|Rutherford]] engine<ref name=rocketlabs-propulsion20160919 />, nine of which power the [[Electron (rocket)|Electron]] rocket<ref name=rocketlabs-propulsion20160919 />, and the electric pump-fed rocket engine used in sounding rockets developed by [[Ventions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ventions.com/menu/|title=Technologies|website=Ventions|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> On 21 January 2018, Electron was the first electric pump-fed rocket to reach orbit.<ref name=nzh20180121>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11979201 |title=Blast off! Rocket Lab successfully reaches orbit |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |last=Ryan |first=Holly |date=21 January 2018 |access-date=21 January 2018}}</ref>
In comparison to turbo-pumped rocket cycles such as [[Staged combustion cycle|staged combustion]] and [[Gas-generator cycle|gas generator]], an electric cycle engine has potentially worse performance due to the added mass of batteries, but may have lower development and manufacturing costs due its mechanical simplicity, its lack of high temperature turbomachinery, and its easier controllability<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aacademica.org/hernan.emilio.tacca/9.pdf|title=Electric feed systems for liquid propellant rocket engines|last=Rachov|first=Pablo|date=2010|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180121184414/https://www.aacademica.org/hernan.emilio.tacca/9.pdf|archive-date=2018-01-21|dead-url=|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref>. Conversely, an electric cycle engine may have significantly better performance than [[Pressure-fed engine (rocket)|pressure-fed rocket engines]] and [[Solid-propellant_rocket|solid propellant rocket motors]].
==See also== * [[Combustion tap-off cycle]] * [[Expander cycle (rocket)|Expander cycle]] * [[Gas-generator cycle]] * [[Pressure-fed engine (rocket)|Pressure-fed engine]] * [[Rocket engine]] * [[Solid-propellant rocket]] * [[Staged combustion cycle (rocket)|Staged combustion cycle]]
