{{pp-protect|small=yes}} {{Refimprove|date=September 2013}} {{Infobox company | logo = Future_Electronics_Official_Logo.png | name = Future Electronics | type = [[Privately held company|Private]] | foundation = 1968 | founder = Robert G. Miller | area_served = Worldwide | num_locations = 169 offices in 44 countries | num_employees = 5,500<ref name=dolan-forbes /> | revenue = $5 billion USD (2014)<ref name=dolan-forbes /> | location = 237 Hymus Boulevard Pointe Claire, Quebec,Canada H9R 5C7 | industry = Electronics | homepage = http://www.futureelectronics.com }}
'''Future Electronics Inc.''' is a distributor of [[electronic component|electronic and electro-mechanical components]] headquartered in [[Pointe-Claire]], [[Quebec]]. Founded in 1968 by Canadian billionaire [[Robert Miller (Future Electronics)|Robert Miller]], the company is one of Quebec's largest privately owned companies<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/memphis/stories/2002/10/28/story5.html |title=DeSoto lands electronics warehouse - Memphis Business Journal |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=2002-10-27 |accessdate=2013-09-04}}</ref> and is currently the fourth largest electronics distributor in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.cmpnet.com/eet/25_distributors_2008/25pg28_29.pdf |title=Top 25 Global Franchised Distributors |publisher=I.cmpnet.com |accessdate=2013-09-04}}</ref> It operates in 169 locations in 44 countries in the Americas, Europe, Asia and Africa.
In 2014 its revenues were $5 billion.<ref name="dolan-forbes">{{cite news|last1=Dolan|first1=Kerry A.|title=Press-Shy Canadian Electronics Billionaire Robert Miller Breaks His Silence|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2014/03/31/press-shy-canadian-electronics-billionaire-robert-miller-breaks-his-silence/|accessdate=15 July 2015|work=Forbes|date=31 March 2014}}</ref> In September 2018, Future Electronics sponsored NXP's free Technology Day in Boston.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.thomasnet.com/companystory/future-electronics-to-sponsor-an-nxp-free-technology-day-in-boston-massachusetts-40015079|title=Future Electronics to Sponsor an NXP Free Technology Day in Boston, Massachusetts|website=news.thomasnet.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-25}}</ref>
[[File:Future-electronics-building-montreal 01.jpg|thumb|Future Electronics Headquarters in Montreal, Canada]]
==1999 police raid== In 1999, the offices of Future Electronics in Montreal were raided by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] following an investigation into allegations that the company had overcharged some customers.<ref>https://www.electronicsweekly.com/news/archived/resources-archived/future-raided-by-mounties-1999-05/</ref> Future denied all charges and the founder and CEO of the company Robert Miller called the raid an "unfounded assault on our integrity".<ref>https://www.forbes.com/global/1999/1227/057_01.html#5dd1bab7a06d</ref> A year after the raid, in December 2000, [[Quebec_Court_of_Appeal|the Quebec Appeal Court]] ruled that the RCMP had no basis for issuing the search warrant executed at Future’s offices.<ref>https://www.electronicsweekly.com/news/archived/resources-archived/court-rules-in-favour-of-future-electronics-over-police-2000-12/</ref> The Quebec Appeal Court ordered the RCMP to return all the documents which were seized from the company.<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/future-electronics-wins-case-over-search-warrant-1.227562</ref> In April 2002, the Office of the US Attorney in Dallas,Texas announced that the investigation had been closed and that no charges would be filed.<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/us-drops-future-electronics-probe/article4133169/</ref>
